  "slug": "choosing-between-solar-pv-and-solar-thermal",
  "title": "Solar PV vs solar thermal: which to fit",
  "subtitle": "Output, versatility, and the UK case for PV over hot water panels",
  "excerpt": "Solar thermal panels heat water directly and are more efficient per square metre than PV. But they only produce hot water, they cannot export, and they cannot charge a battery. Solar PV produces electricity that can do all three. In the UK, PV is the right choice for most households unless hot water is the dominant energy cost.",
  "type": "TECHNIQUE",
  "sourceNotes": "Energy Saving Trust solar thermal vs solar PV comparison (2024). BRE solar thermal yield data. MCS MCS 012 solar thermal installation standard.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "Solar thermal",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpba3aug000n4ov4xjp163bc"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " collectors turn 60 to 70 per cent of sunlight into useful heat. ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "Solar PV",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpba3atq000m4ov4qsct2dv5"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " turns 20 to 23 per cent of sunlight into electricity. Per square metre, thermal is more efficient. But electricity is more flexible than hot water. It can power lights and appliances, run an immersion heater, charge a battery, run an electric car, or be sold back to the grid.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "UK annual yield comparison",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Solar thermal, 4 m² flat plate: approximately 1,400-1,800 kWh of useful heat per year (southern England). Provides 50-60% of a household's hot water over a full year.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Solar PV, 4 m² (approx 2 × 400 W panels = 0.8",
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": []
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Solar PV at 4 kWp (16-18 m²): 3,400-4,000 kWh/year of electricity, of which roughly half can be self-consumed directly.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "When thermal makes sense",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Roof space is very limited (less than 6 m²), thermal delivers more heat per square metre than PV.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "High hot water demand (large family, no gas connection, immersion heater as primary source).",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Already have a system installed with a compatible twin-coil cylinder.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Why PV wins for most households",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "PV output can be diverted to hot water via an immersion diverter, replicating most of what thermal does.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "PV earns export income via the Smart Export Guarantee. Thermal cannot.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "PV is compatible with battery storage. Thermal excess in summer cannot be usefully stored.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Solar thermal requires a twin-coil cylinder and often a controller, pump, and expansion vessel. PV requires fewer ancillary components.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Cost per",
                    "type": "text"
                  },
                  {
                    "text": "kWp",
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termId": "cmpba3aj300074ov4m7mg0qnc"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "text": "has fallen substantially for PV; solar thermal has not followed the same cost curve.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
